==English==

===Etymology 1===
From [[Old Norse]] ''bekkr'' a stream or [[brook]].  Cognate with German [[:de:Bach|Bach]].

====Noun====
'''beck'''
# (Northern England) a stream or small river.

=====Synonyms=====
*[[brook]]
*[[burn]]
*[[creek]]
*[[stream]]

===Etymology 2===
A shortened form of '''[[beckon]]''', from [[Old English]] ''bēcnan'', [[Germanic]] ''baukna'' [[beacon]].

====Noun====
'''beck'''
# A significant nod, or motion of the head or hand, especially as a call or command.
#: ''To be at the '''beck''' and call of someone.''

